children.text: This dwelling is in a designated termite zone, and there has not been adequate clearance of at least 400mm provided under the sub-floor services to the ground, resulting in a damp environment, which according to the BCA, encourages timber rot, fungus growth and the potential for termite activity.
Part 3.1.4.3 Termite management systems of the NCC’s Building Code of Australia (BCA) requires that
‘Where a termite management system is required it must comply with AS 3660.1’ .
The relevant Australian Standard AS 3660.1 Termite Management states in clause 3.3.2 Access for visual inspection, that
‘A minimum clearance of 400mm between finished ground level and any structural
components or other obstructions (e.g. bearers, joists, plumbing fixtures or ducting systems)’ ;

As the building surveyor has determined that this dwelling is in a designated termite zone, the builder will need to extend the ground clearances to a minimum of 400mm to comply with the requirements of the BCA and AS 3660.
